 PNAS. 2008 Aug 12;105(32):11270-5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nPathological expression of CXCL12 at the blood-brain barrier correlates with severity of multiple sclerosis. McCandless EE, Piccio L, Woerner BM, Schmidt RE, Rubin JB, Cross AH, Klein RS. The American Journal of Pathology. 2008 Mar;172(3):799-808.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nCXCR3 mediates region-specific antiviral T cell trafficking within the central nervous system during West Nile virus encephalitis. Zhang B, Chan YK, Lu B, Diamond MS, Klein RS. Journal of Immunology. 2008 Feb 15;180(4):2641-9.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nMolecular targets for disrupting leukocyte trafficking during multiple sclerosis. McCandless EE, Klein RS. Expert Reviews in Molecular Medicine. 2007 Jul 19;9(20):1-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nCXCL12 limits inflammation by localizing mononuclear infiltrates to the perivascular space during experimental autoimmune encephalomyelitis. McCandless EE, Wang Q, Woerner BM, Harper JM, Klein RS. Journal of Immunology. 2006 Dec 1;177(11):8053-64.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nNeuronal CXCL10 directs CD8+ T-cell recruitment and control of West Nile virus encephalitis. Klein RS, Lin E, Zhang B, Luster AD, Tollett J, Samuel MA, Engle M, Diamond MS. Journal of Virology. 2005 Sep;79(17):11457-66.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n=== References ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American neuroimmunologist}}\n{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n{{cleanup|reason=duplicate citations, [[WP:NAMEDREFS]] are needed.|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Robyn Klein\n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = \n| nationality       = American\n| fields            = Neuroimmunology\n| workplaces        = Washington University in St. Louis, Missouri\n| alma_mater        = Barnard College, Albert Einstein College of Medicine, Brigham and Women's Hospital, Massachusetts General Hospital\n| known_for         = Microglial mediated memory loss in West Nile Virus, sex-differences in Multiple Sclerosis\n| awards            = Dana Foundation Award for Neuroimmunology \nDistinguished Educator Award, Washington University\n}}\n\n'''Robyn Klein''' is an American neuroimmunologist as well as the vice provost and associate dean of graduate education at [[Washington University in St. Louis|Washington University]] in St. Louis Missouri. Klein is also a professor in the Departments of Medicine, Anatomy & Neurobiology, and Pathology & Immunology. Her research explores the pathogenesis of [[neuroinflammation]] in the [[central nervous system]] by probing how immune signalling molecules regulate [[Blood\u2013brain barrier|blood brain barrier]] permeability. Klein is also a fervent advocate for gender equity in STEM and is the president of the Academic Women\u2019s Network at the [[Washington University in St. Louis|Washington University]] School of Medicine.\n\n== Early Life and Education ==\nKlein pursued her undergraduate studies at [[Columbia University]]\u2019s [[Barnard College]] in [[New York City|New York]] City.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://infectiousdiseases.wustl.edu/faculty-staff/robyn-s-klein/|title=Robyn S. Klein, MD, PhD|website=Infectious Diseases|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> In 1985, Klein completing her Bachelors of Arts in Biological Sciences, graduating with honors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cell-symposia.com/neuroimmunology-2019/bio-klein.asp|title=Organizer: Cell Symposia Neuro-Immune Axis: Reciprocal Regulation in Development, Health, and Disease|website=www.cell-symposia.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> After her undergraduate degree, Klein pursued an MD-PhD at [[Albert Einstein College of Medicine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cell-symposia.com/neuroimmunology-2019/bio-klein.asp|title=Organizer: Cell Symposia Neuro-Immune Axis: Reciprocal Regulation in Development, Health, and Disease|website=www.cell-symposia.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> On her way to obtaining both her dual-degree, Klein completed a Masters in Neuroscience ion 1990 at [[Albert Einstein College of Medicine|Albert Einstein College]] and then graduated in 1993 with a Ph.D. in Neuroscience and an M.D. from Albert Einstein.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://infectiousdiseases.wustl.edu/faculty-staff/robyn-s-klein/|title=Robyn S. Klein, MD, PhD|website=Infectious Diseases|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Klein then completed her internship and her residency at the [[Brigham and Women's Hospital|Brigham and Women\u2019s Hospital]] in Boston, Massachusetts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isniweb.org/klein-robyn/|title=Klein, Robyn|language=it-IT|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Throughout her experiences in the clinic, Klein noticed that many of her [[HIV/AIDS|Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome]] ([[HIV/AIDS|AIDS]]) patients had faced severe brain infections in their immune compromised state and began to wonder how brain inflammation and infection were associated with systemic viral infections and how that could be treated in the clinic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/washington-people-robyn-klein/|title=Washington People: Robyn Klein|date=2018-08-28|website=Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nFollowing these clinical experiences and inspirations, Klein completed her fellowship in Infectious Disease at [[Massachusetts General Hospital]] and then completed her postdoctoral training in Immunology at [[Harvard Medical School|Harvard Medical Schoo]]<nowiki/>l under the mentorship of Dr. [[Andrew D. Luster|Andrew Luster]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isniweb.org/klein-robyn/|title=Klein, Robyn|language=it-IT|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> In 1999, Klein published a first author paper in The Journal of Immunology where she explored the role of [[chemokine]]s in the development of [[HIV|Human Immunodeficiency Virus]] (HIV) associated [[dementia]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Klein|first=Robyn S.|last2=Williams|first2=Kenneth C.|last3=Alvarez-Hernandez|first3=Xavier|last4=Westmoreland|first4=Susan|last5=Force|first5=Thomas|last6=Lackner|first6=Andrew A.|last7=Luster|first7=Andrew D.|date=1999-08-01|title=Chemokine Receptor Expression and Signaling in Macaque and Human Fetal Neurons and Astrocytes: Implications for the Neuropathogenesis of AIDS|url=https://www.jimmunol.org/content/163/3/1636|journal=The Journal of Immunology|language=en|volume=163|issue=3|pages=1636\u20131646|issn=0022-1767|pmid=10415069}}</ref> She found that after infection with HIV, neurons and astrocytes has increased expression of chemokine receptors and stimulation of these receptors causes increased calcium influx in these cells, but blocking these receptors with specific ligands can ameliorate this effect.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Klein|first=Robyn S.|last2=Williams|first2=Kenneth C.|last3=Alvarez-Hernandez|first3=Xavier|last4=Westmoreland|first4=Susan|last5=Force|first5=Thomas|last6=Lackner|first6=Andrew A.|last7=Luster|first7=Andrew D.|date=1999-08-01|title=Chemokine Receptor Expression and Signaling in Macaque and Human Fetal Neurons and Astrocytes: Implications for the Neuropathogenesis of AIDS|url=https://www.jimmunol.org/content/163/3/1636|journal=The Journal of Immunology|language=en|volume=163|issue=3|pages=1636\u20131646|issn=0022-1767|pmid=10415069}}</ref> Her work suggested that, similar to leukocytes, chemokine signalling during viral infection might mediate neuronal and astrocytic dysfunction in HIV associated dementias.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Klein|first=Robyn S.|last2=Williams|first2=Kenneth C.|last3=Alvarez-Hernandez|first3=Xavier|last4=Westmoreland|first4=Susan|last5=Force|first5=Thomas|last6=Lackner|first6=Andrew A.|last7=Luster|first7=Andrew D.|date=1999-08-01|title=Chemokine Receptor Expression and Signaling in Macaque and Human Fetal Neurons and Astrocytes: Implications for the Neuropathogenesis of AIDS|url=https://www.jimmunol.org/content/163/3/1636|journal=The Journal of Immunology|language=en|volume=163|issue=3|pages=1636\u20131646|issn=0022-1767|pmid=10415069}}</ref> In 2002, Klein helped discover that deficiency in Chemokine Receptor 2 (CCR2) decreased monocyte recruitment to the CNS which help reduce the symptoms of experimental autoimmune encephalitis.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Izikson|first=Leonid|last2=Klein|first2=Robyn S.|last3=Charo|first3=Israel F.|last4=Weiner|first4=Howard L.|last5=Luster|first5=Andrew D.|date=2000-10-02|title=Resistance to Experimental Autoimmune Encephalomyelitis in Mice Lacking the Cc Chemokine Receptor (Ccr2)|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2193310/|journal=The Journal of Experimental Medicine|volume=192|issue=7|pages=1075\u20131080|issn=0022-1007|pmc=2193310|pmid=11015448}}</ref> In Klein\u2019s first author paper in Development in 2001, she reported that the chemokine CXC12 and its receptor CXCR4 are important in cerebellar granule cell proliferation and migration.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Klein|first=R. S.|last2=Rubin|first2=J. B.|last3=Gibson|first3=H. D.|last4=DeHaan|first4=E. N.|last5=Alvarez-Hernandez|first5=X.|last6=Segal|first6=R. A.|last7=Luster|first7=A. D.|date=June 2001|title=SDF-1 alpha induces chemotaxis and enhances Sonic hedgehog-induced proliferation of cerebellar granule cells|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11493520|journal=Development (Cambridge, England)|volume=128|issue=11|pages=1971\u20131981|issn=0950-1991|pmid=11493520}}</ref> Klein\u2019s work has continually shown that immune signalling in the brain contributes to brain disease pathogenesis and cognitive defects that could be treated with immune targeting therapies.\n\n== Career and Research ==\nAfter Klein completed her postdoctoral work, she was recruited to Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis, Missouri in 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cell-symposia.com/neuroimmunology-2019/bio-klein.asp|title=Organizer: Cell Symposia Neuro-Immune Axis: Reciprocal Regulation in Development, Health, and Disease|website=www.cell-symposia.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> At WUSM, Klein was appointed, and still holds, professorships in the Departments of Medicine, Pathology & Immunology, and Neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cell-symposia.com/neuroimmunology-2019/bio-klein.asp|title=Organizer: Cell Symposia Neuro-Immune Axis: Reciprocal Regulation in Development, Health, and Disease|website=www.cell-symposia.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> After Klein arrived at WUSM, she founded the Center for Neuroimmunology and Neuroinfectious Diseases and now directs the center.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cell-symposia.com/neuroimmunology-2019/bio-klein.asp|title=Organizer: Cell Symposia Neuro-Immune Axis: Reciprocal Regulation in Development, Health, and Disease|website=www.cell-symposia.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> In order to train the next leaders in neuroimmunology, Klein also developed a neuroimmunology basic and translational science research program where scientists work to probe the neuroimmune mechanisms underlying the pathogenesis of brain related diseases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cell-symposia.com/neuroimmunology-2019/bio-klein.asp|title=Organizer: Cell Symposia Neuro-Immune Axis: Reciprocal Regulation in Development, Health, and Disease|website=www.cell-symposia.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> In 2017, Klein was named the vice provost and assistant dean of graduate education for the Division of Biology and Biomedical Sciences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/klein-named-vice-provost-associate-dean-graduate-education/|title=Klein named vice provost and associate dean for graduate education|date=2017-07-20|website=Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> In addition to promoting departmental collaborations and ensuring that graduate students are supported in their pursuits of a variety of different career paths, Klein is focusing on improving diversity and equity in the program by recruiting students from underrepresented groups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/klein-named-vice-provost-associate-dean-graduate-education/|title=Klein named vice provost and associate dean for graduate education|date=2017-07-20|website=Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> These goals are in line with Kleins past achievements and involvements in advocating for diversity and equity in science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/klein-named-vice-provost-associate-dean-graduate-education/|title=Klein named vice provost and associate dean for graduate education|date=2017-07-20|website=Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> She is the co-director of the [[Amgen]] Scholars Program at [[Washington University in St. Louis|Washington University]] ensuring that a diverse group of undergraduate students have the opportunity to experience science in top labs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/university-receives-new-grant-to-fund-amgen-scholars-program/|title=University receives new grant to fund Amgen Scholars Program|date=2018-12-07|website=Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Further, as the president of the Academic Women\u2019s Network at the Washington University School of Medicine, Klein promotes career development and mentorship for women in science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/klein-named-vice-provost-associate-dean-graduate-education/|title=Robyn S. Klein|website=Diversity & Inclusion|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Klein has conducted research on gender bias in conference organization, highlighting the fact that conference committee composition matters in the selection of diverse speakers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/study-accomplished-female-scientists-often-overlooked/|title=Study: Accomplished female scientists often overlooked|date=2017-04-20|website=Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Klein reports that \u201cnaming the problem is the first step in solving it\u201d, suggesting that conducting quantitative studies on gender bias in scientific meetings, hiring, acceptances, grant awards etc. will be the first step towards actually solving these issues and increasing representation in science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/study-accomplished-female-scientists-often-overlooked/|title=Study: Accomplished female scientists often overlooked|date=2017-04-20|website=Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nIn Klein\u2019s Lab, the research is focused on exploring the effects of immune signalling on brain disease pathogenesis and eventually developing targets for future disease treatments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hopecenter.wustl.edu/?faculty=robyn-klein-md-phd|title=Robyn Klein, MD, PhD|website=The Hope Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Her lab has focused on two main mechanisms with which the immune system signals to and interactions with the central nervous system: the first is through leukocytes infiltrating the brain and the second is through cytokines and chemokines directly affecting neuronal function.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hopecenter.wustl.edu/?faculty=robyn-klein-md-phd|title=Robyn Klein, MD, PhD|website=The Hope Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Her lab has extensively explored how cytokines and chemokines affect blood brain barrier permeability and how West Nile Virus causes encephalitis in the brain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hopecenter.wustl.edu/?faculty=robyn-klein-md-phd|title=Robyn Klein, MD, PhD|website=The Hope Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> West Nile Virus has been shown to cause significant brain damage leading to memory loss and Klein\u2019s lab researches ways to prevent this from occurring.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://source.wustl.edu/2016/06/memory-loss-caused-west-nile-virus-explained/|title=Memory loss caused by West Nile virus explained {{!}} The Source {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|date=2016-06-22|website=The Source|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> She found that microglia, the brain\u2019s innate immune cells,\u00a0 accumulate around neurons at the site of infection and complement protein is also highly expressed at the site of infection.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vasek|first=Michael J.|last2=Garber|first2=Charise|last3=Dorsey|first3=Denise|last4=Durrant|first4=Douglas M.|last5=Bollman|first5=Bryan|last6=Soung|first6=Allison|last7=Yu|first7=Jinsheng|last8=Perez-Torres|first8=Carlos|last9=Frouin|first9=Arnaud|last10=Wilton|first10=Daniel K.|last11=Funk|first11=Kristen|date=June 2016|title=A complement\u2013microglial axis drives synapse loss during virus-induced memory impairment|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nature18283|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=534|issue=7608|pages=538\u2013543|doi=10.1038/nature18283|issn=1476-4687}}</ref> Both of these findings signify increased neuronal pruning and destruction by microglia leading to memory loss in patients with West Nile Virus infections.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vasek|first=Michael J.|last2=Garber|first2=Charise|last3=Dorsey|first3=Denise|last4=Durrant|first4=Douglas M.|last5=Bollman|first5=Bryan|last6=Soung|first6=Allison|last7=Yu|first7=Jinsheng|last8=Perez-Torres|first8=Carlos|last9=Frouin|first9=Arnaud|last10=Wilton|first10=Daniel K.|last11=Funk|first11=Kristen|date=June 2016|title=A complement\u2013microglial axis drives synapse loss during virus-induced memory impairment|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nature18283|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=534|issue=7608|pages=538\u2013543|doi=10.1038/nature18283|issn=1476-4687}}</ref> Further, Klein found that these microglia remain active long after infection clears leading to post-infection inflammation and further synapse loss.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://source.wustl.edu/2016/06/memory-loss-caused-west-nile-virus-explained/|title=Memory loss caused by West Nile virus explained {{!}} The Source {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|date=2016-06-22|website=The Source|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Klein\u2019s Lab has also found, in 2014, that multiple sclerosis (MS) disproportionally effects women compared to men due to higher expression of a blood vessel receptor protein S1PR2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://source.wustl.edu/2014/05/study-helps-explain-why-ms-is-more-common-in-women/|title=Study helps explain why MS is more common in women {{!}} The Source {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|date=2014-05-08|website=The Source|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Further, this protein was expressed at even higher levels in MS patients in brain regions more affected by MS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://source.wustl.edu/2014/05/study-helps-explain-why-ms-is-more-common-in-women/|title=Study helps explain why MS is more common in women {{!}} The Source {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|date=2014-05-08|website=The Source|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>  Klein\u2019s lab has recently begun exploring how inflammatory brain events and immune signalling regulate neural stem cell proliferation, localization, and differentiation in the brain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hopecenter.wustl.edu/?faculty=robyn-klein-md-phd|title=Robyn Klein, MD, PhD|website=The Hope Center|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nAnother overarching goal of the Klein lab is to understand how glial cells regulate T cell activity in viral infections and autoimmune inflammation in the brain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/research/|title=Research {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Her research in these areas has highlighted the extensive communication between astrocytes and T cells such that astrocytes play a critical role in trafficking T cells throughout the CNS during disease.\n\n== Memberships ==\n\n* American College of Physicians<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/klein-named-vice-provost-associate-dean-graduate-education/|title=Klein named vice provost and associate dean for graduate education|date=2017-07-20|website=Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n* American Society for Microbiology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/klein-named-vice-provost-associate-dean-graduate-education/|title=Klein named vice provost and associate dean for graduate education|date=2017-07-20|website=Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n* American Society for Immunology and the International Society for Neuroimmunology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/klein-named-vice-provost-associate-dean-graduate-education/|title=Klein named vice provost and associate dean for graduate education|date=2017-07-20|website=Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n* President of the Academic Women\u2019s Network at the School of Medicine<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/klein-named-vice-provost-associate-dean-graduate-education/|title=Klein named vice provost and associate dean for graduate education|date=2017-07-20|website=Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n* Elected Member of the International Advisory Board of the International Society of Neuroimmunology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/klein-named-vice-provost-associate-dean-graduate-education/|title=Klein named vice provost and associate dean for graduate education|date=2017-07-20|website=Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n* Founding member of the International Society for Neurovirology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/klein-named-vice-provost-associate-dean-graduate-education/|title=Klein named vice provost and associate dean for graduate education|date=2017-07-20|website=Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and Honors ==\n\n* 2020 Distinguished Educator Award of Graduate Education at Washington University<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/2020-distinguished-faculty-awards-announced/|title=2020 Distinguished Faculty Awards announced|date=2020-03-05|website=Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n* 2017 Dana Foundation Award for Neuroimmunology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.wustl.edu/news/klein-named-vice-provost-associate-dean-graduate-education/|title=Klein named vice provost and associate dean for graduate education|date=2017-07-20|website=Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\nEncephalitic Alphaviruses Exploit Caveola-Mediated Transcytosis at the Blood-Brain Barrier for Central Nervous System Entry. Samili H, Cain MD, Jiang X, Roth RA, Beatty W, Sun C, Klimstra WB, Hou J, Klein RS. mBio. 2020 Feb 11;11(1).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nAstrocyte-T cell crosstalk regulates region-specific neuroinflammation. Williams JL*, Manivasagam S*, Smith BC, Sim J, Vollmer LL, Daniels BP, Russell JH, Klein RS. Glia. 2020 Jan 21.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nMechanisms of Pathogen Invasion into the Central Nervous System. Cain MD, Salimi H, Diamond MS, Klein RS. Neuron. 2019 Sep 4;103(5):771-783.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nT cells promote microglia-mediated synaptic elimination and cognitive dysfunction during recovery from neuropathogenic flaviviruses. Garber C*, Soung A*, Vollmer LL, Kanmogne M, Last A, Brown J, Klein RS. Nature Neuroscience. 2019 Aug;22(8):1276-1288.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nNeuroinflammation During RNA Viral Infections. Klein RS, Garber C, Funk KE, Salimi H, Soung A, Kanmogne M, Manivasagam S, Agner S, Cain M. Annual Review of Immunology. 2019 Apr 26;37:73-95.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nCSF1R antagonism limits local restimulation of antiviral CD8+ T cells during viral encephalitis. Funk KE, Klein RS. Journal of Neuroinflammation. 2019 Jan 31;16(1):22.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nAstrocytes decrease adult neurogenesis during virus-induced memory dysfunction via IL-1. Garber C*, Vasek MJ*, Vollmer LL, Sun T, Jiang X, Klein RS. Nature Immunology. 2018 Feb;19(2):151-161.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nVirus entry and replication in the brain precedes blood-brain barrier disruption during intranasal alphavirus infection. Cain MD, Salimi H, Gong Y, Yang L, Hamilton SL, Heffernan JR, Hou J, Miller MJ, Klein RS. Journal of Neuroimmunology. 2017 Jul 15;308:118-130.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nSpeaking out about gender imbalance in invited speakers improves diversity. Klein RS, Voskuhl R, Segal BM, Dittel BN, Lane TE, Bethea JR, Carson MJ, Colton C, Rosi S, Anderson A, Piccio L, Goverman JM, Benveniste EN, Brown MA, Tiwari-Woodruff SK, Harris TH, Cross AH. Nature Immunology. 2017 Apr 18;18(5):475-478.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nInfectious immunity in the central nervous system and brain function. Klein RS, Garber C, Howard N. Nature Immunology. 2017 Feb;18(2):132-141.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nA complement-microglial axis drives synapse loss during virus-induced memory impairment. Vasek MJ, Garber C, Dorsey D, Durrant DM, Bollman B, Soung A, Yu J, Perez-Torres C, Frouin A, Wilton DK, Funk K, DeMasters BK, Jiang X, Bowen JR, Mennerick S, Robinson JK, Garbow JR, Tyler KL, Suthar MS, Schmidt RE, Stevens B, Klein RS. Nature. 2016 Jun;534(7608):538-43.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nCCR5 limits cortical viral loads during West Nile virus infection of the central nervous system. Durrant DM, Daniels BP, Pasieka T, Dorsey D, Klein RS. Journal of Neuroinflammation. 2015 Dec 15;12:233.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nIL-1R1 signaling regulates CXCL12-mediated T cell localization and fate within the central nervous system during West Nile Virus encephalitis. Durrant DM, Daniels BP, Klein RS. Journal of Immunology. 2014 Oct 15;193(8):4095-106.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nIL-1R1 is required for dendritic cell-mediated T cell reactivation within the CNS during West Nile virus encephalitis. Durrant DM, Robinette ML, Klein RS. Journal of Experimental Medicine. 2013 Mar 11;210(3):503-16.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nImmortalized human cerebral microvascular endothelial cells maintain the properties of primary cells in an in vitro model of immune migration across the blood brain barrier. Daniels BP, Cruz-Orengo L, Pasieka TJ, Couraud PO, Romero IA, Weksler B, Cooper JA, Doering TL, Klein RS. Journal of Neuroscience Methods. 2013 Jan 15;212(1):173-9.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nCXCR7 antagonism prevents axonal injury during experimental autoimmune encephalomyelitis as revealed by in vivo axial diffusivity. Cruz-Orengo L, Chen YJ, Kim JH, Dorsey D, Song SK, Klein RS. Journal of Neuroinflammation. 2011 Dec 6;8:170.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nCXCR7 influences leukocyte entry into the CNS parenchyma by controlling abluminal CXCL12 abundance during autoimmunity. Cruz-Orengo L, Holman DW, Dorsey D, Zhou L, Zhang P, Wright M, McCandless EE, Patel JR, Luker GD, Littman DR, Russell JH, Klein RS. Journal of Experimental Medicine. 2011 Feb 14;208(2):327-39.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nTNF-alpha-dependent regulation of CXCR3 expression modulates neuronal survival during West Nile virus encephalitis. Zhang B, Patel J, Croyle M, Diamond MS, Klein RS. Journal of Neuroimmunology. 2010 Jul 27;224(1-2):28-38.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nCXCR4 antagonism increases T cell trafficking in the central nervous system and improves survival from West Nile virus encephalitis. McCandless EE, Zhang B, Diamond MS, Klein RS. PNAS. 2008 Aug 12;105(32):11270-5.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nPathological expression of CXCL12 at the blood-brain barrier correlates with severity of multiple sclerosis. McCandless EE, Piccio L, Woerner BM, Schmidt RE, Rubin JB, Cross AH, Klein RS. The American Journal of Pathology. 2008 Mar;172(3):799-808.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nCXCR3 mediates region-specific antiviral T cell trafficking within the central nervous system during West Nile virus encephalitis. Zhang B, Chan YK, Lu B, Diamond MS, Klein RS. Journal of Immunology. 2008 Feb 15;180(4):2641-9.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nMolecular targets for disrupting leukocyte trafficking during multiple sclerosis. McCandless EE, Klein RS. Expert Reviews in Molecular Medicine. 2007 Jul 19;9(20):1-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nCXCL12 limits inflammation by localizing mononuclear infiltrates to the perivascular space during experimental autoimmune encephalomyelitis. McCandless EE, Wang Q, Woerner BM, Harper JM, Klein RS. Journal of Immunology. 2006 Dec 1;177(11):8053-64.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nNeuronal CXCL10 directs CD8+ T-cell recruitment and control of West Nile virus encephalitis. Klein RS, Lin E, Zhang B, Luster AD, Tollett J, Samuel MA, Engle M, Diamond MS. Journal of Virology. 2005 Sep;79(17):11457-66.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kleinlab.wustl.edu/publications/|title=Publications {{!}} Robyn Klein Lab {{!}} Washington University in St. Louis|website=kleinlab.wustl.edu|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n==== References ====\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Kj cheetham", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Minor formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robyn_Klein"}
{"title_page": "Wuhan Metro", "text_new": "{{Infobox Public transit\n| name = Wuhan Metro\n| image = Wuhan Metro Logo.svg\n| imagesize = 75px\n| image2 = Rolling stock NO. A62 of Wuhan Metro Line 1.jpg\n| imagesize2 = 300px\n| caption2=The train of Line 1 departing from [[Zongguan Station]]\n| locale = [[Wuhan]]\n| transit_type = [[Rapid transit]]\n| began_operation = {{Start date and age|2004|07|28|df=yes}}\n| suspension = {{Start date and age|2020|01|23|df=yes}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.ifeng.com/c/7tSrfZdR1Ki|script-title=zh:\u76f4\u51fb\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1\u505c\u8fd0\uff1a10\u70b9\u4e00\u5230\u6240\u6709\u5730\u94c1\u7ad9\u53ea\u51fa\u4e0d\u8fdb\uff0c\u5b89\u68c0\u5458\u5173\u673a\u79bb\u5c97}}</ref>  due to the outbreak of [[SARS-CoV-2]] virus\n| resumed_operation = {{Start date and age|2020|03|28|df=yes}} on selected lines\n| system_length = {{convert|339|km|mi|1|abbr=on}}<ref name=Wuhan8-3 />\n| lines = 9\n| train_length = 4 or 6 cars\n| vehicles = \n| stations = 228<ref name=Wuhan8-3 />\n| ridership = *3.642 million (April 2019)<ref name=\u5168\u6765\u4e86\uff012019\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u5730\u94c1\u5ba2\u8fd0\u91cf\u603b\u7ed3>{{Cite web |url = https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/7aCHDocl1-JvLA9QEJPQsw |script-title=zh:\u5168\u6765\u4e86\uff012019\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u5730\u94c1\u5ba2\u8fd0\u91cf\u603b\u7ed3 |author =[[WeChat]]@\u5730\u94c1\u5ba2\u6d41\u53ca\u8fd0\u8f93\u7814\u7a76\u963f\u725b |date = 2020-02-15 |publisher = \u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u534f\u4f1a }}</ref> \n*4.465 million (Maximum, 4 April 2019)<ref name=\"peak ridership\">{{cite web |url=https://m.sohu.com/a/306708478_664673/?pvid=000115_3w_a&sec=wd|script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1\u6e05\u660e\u5c0f\u957f\u5047\u9001\u5ba21615\u4e07\u4e58\u6b21\uff0c\u5ba2\u6d41\u91cf42\u5929\u5185\u4e09\u521b\u7eaa\u5f55}}</ref>\n| annual_ridership = 1.22 billion (2019)<ref name=\u5168\u6765\u4e86\uff012019\u5e74\u4e2d\u56fd\u57ce\u5e02\u5730\u94c1\u5ba2\u8fd0\u91cf\u603b\u7ed3></ref>\n| track_gauge = {{Track gauge|sg|allk=on}}\n| reporting marks = \n| operator = Wuhan Metro Co., Ltd.\n| owner = Wuhan Metro Co., Ltd.\n| website = {{url|www.wuhanrt.com|www.wuhanrt.com}}\n| map = [[File:Route Map of Wuhan Metro.svg|300px]]\n| alt = \n| head_office =77 Huanle Avenue, Hongshan District, Wuhan\n| caption = \n| area served = \n| line_number = \n| start = \n| headway =2.5 - 9 min\n| end = \n| chief_executive = \n| character = Elevated and underground\n| map_state = \n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|s2=\u6b66\u6c49\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\n|t2=\u6b66\u6f22\u8ecc\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\n|p2=W\u01d4h\u00e0n Gu\u01d0d\u00e0o Ji\u0101ot\u014dng\n|s=\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1\n|t=\u6b66\u6f22\u5730\u9435\n|p=W\u01d4h\u00e0n D\u00ecti\u011b\n|order=st\n}}\nThe '''Wuhan Metro''' is a [[rapid transit]] system serving the city of [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China, operated by the [[Wuhan Metro Co., Ltd]]. \nThe system began operation on July 28, 2004 with the completion of a ten-station long elevated line between [[Huangpu Road Station|Huangpu Road]] and [[Zongguan Station|Zongguan]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ctdsb.cnhubei.com/html/ctdsb/20110409/ctdsb1348512.html |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u8f7b\u8f68\u4eca\u8fce\u7b2c1\u4ebf\u540d\u4e58\u5ba2 |script-work=zh:\u8346\u695a\u7f51-\u695a\u5929\u90fd\u5e02\u62a5 |language=Chinese |date=April 9, 2011}}</ref> making Wuhan the sixth city in [[mainland China]] to have a metro system after [[Beijing Subway|Beijing]], [[Tianjin Metro|Tianjin]], [[Shanghai Metro|Shanghai]], [[Guangzhou Metro|Guangzhou]] and [[Dalian Metro|Dalian]].<ref>[http://urbanrail.net/as/wuha/wuhan.htm Wuhan], ''UrbanRail.net''</ref> Line 1 is the first metro line in China to have been wrongly referred to as a light rail ({{zh|labels=no |s=\u8f7b\u8f68 |p=q\u012bng gu\u01d0}}) system in Chinese terminology.<ref>Wuhan, along with other three Chinese cities, has been the first batch to be approved to build so-called \"light rail\" system in China since 2000, see {{cite web |url=http://news.huochepiao.com/2012-7/20127177020183.htm |script-title=zh:2000\u5e74\uff0c\u56fd\u5bb6\u6279\u51c6\u957f\u6625\u3001\u5927\u8fde\u3001\u6b66\u6c49\u548c\u91cd\u5e864\u4e2a\u57ce\u5e02\u4e3a\u9996\u6279\u8f7b\u8f68\u5efa\u8bbe\u793a\u8303\u57ce\u5e02}}. However, [[Changchun]] built a true light-rail system, [[Dalian]] built a metro-style commuter rail system (and is referred to as {{zh|s=\u5feb\u8f68 |p=ku\u00e0i gu\u01d0}}, not {{zh|links=no |s=\u8f7b\u8f68 |p=q\u012bng gu\u01d0}}), and [[Chongqing]] opted for a monorail system, whereas Wuhan was the only one to build an elevated metro system. See [http://urbanrail.net/as/wuha/wuhan.htm \"Urbanrail--Wuhan\"] and affiliated Wikipedia pages. See also a comment from He Jibin, an Urban Planning official from Wuhan Municipality: \"{{lang|zh-Hans|\u4e0d\u8981\u8ba4\u4e3a\u5730\u4e0b\u7684\u624d\u662f\u5730\u94c1\uff0c1\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e5f\u662f\u5730\u94c1\u7684\u4e00\u79cd\u65b9\u5f0f...\u4f55\u7ee7\u658c\u5f00\u95e8\u89c1\u5c71\u5730\u7ea0\u6b63\u6982\u5ff5\uff0c\u4ed6\u662f\u6b66\u6c49\u5e02\u56fd\u571f\u89c4\u5212\u5c40\u4ea4\u901a\u5e02\u653f\u5904\u5904\u957f\u2026\u2026}}\" {{cite journal | url=http://dawuhan.cnhubei.com/ |script-title=zh:\u90a3\u4e9b\u5e74\uff0c\u6211\u4eec\u4e00\u8d77\u8ffd\u7684\u5730\u94c1 | author=Li Fei (\u674e\u6590) |script-journal=zh:\u5927\u6b66\u6c49 |date=March 2012 | volume=148 | page=33}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2019|November}}, there are 9 lines in operation, totaling 228 stations and {{Convert|339|km|mi}} of system length.<ref name=Wuhan8-3 />\n\nWuhan Metro is pursuing ambitious expansion projects to connect Wuhan's three boroughs, divided by the [[Yangtze River]] and [[Han River (Hubei)|Han River]], to accommodate increasing inter-borough traffic and provide commuter services to suburban [[Satellite city|satellite cities]]. Its future expansion includes the operation of 12 urban lines and 13 suburban lines, totaling a length of {{convert|1045|km|mi}}, making it one of the most expansive rail transit systems in the world. As of 2017, there are currently 13 subway expansion projects totaling {{convert|304|km|abbr=on}} of subway being constructed.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://m.xinhuanet.com/hb/2018-10/01/c_1123512458.htm |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c17\u53f7\u7ebf11\u53f7\u7ebf\u4eca\u65e5\u5f00\u901a \u957f\u6c5f\u516c\u94c1\u96a7\u9053\u540c\u65f6\u542f\u7528|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=2018-10-08}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 January 2020, the Wuhan metro was suspended due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/01/22/798602296/public-transport-in-wuhan-suspended-due-to-coronavirus-concerns|title=Public Transport In Wuhan Suspended Due To Coronavirus Concerns|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref> The operation of Line 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 7  were partially resumed in March 28th.<ref name=\"resume\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2020-03/25/c_138914547.htm|title=Wuhan buses hit the road after two-month lockdown|website=Xinhua|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Wuhan_Metro_Timelapse2019.gif|thumb|400px|Evolution of the Wuhan Metro]]\n\nPreliminary studies of urban rail transit system were prompted by the city shortly after a [[National Railway Company of Belgium|Belgian Railways]] delegation visit in 1984. Following the demolition of old [[Beijing-Hankou Railway]], the city of [[Wuhan]] planned to utilize the corridor to construct the city's first rapid transit rail line. In September 1992, the [[Wuhan Metro Construction Group]] was established by [[Wuhan Municipal Construction Commission]] and a supervision group, led by the mayor [[Qian Yunlu]], was subsequently formed in 1993 to facilitate the project's funding, planning, logistics, and organization. Yet, it was seven years before the city was able to fund construction.\n\nIn October 1999, the [[National Development and Reform Commission|National Planning Commission]] (predecessor of the National Development and Reform Commission) approved the Wuhan \"Light Rail\" project (Line 1, phase 1), signaling the start of serious work on the rail transit project. On October 2, 2000, the [[Wuhan|Wuhan Municipal Government]] ratified the establishment of the [[Wuhan Rail Transit Co., Ltd]]., and contracted construction, operation, administration and related real estate development to the corporation.\n\nIn December 2000, the National Planning Commission accepted a feasibility report on the project and approved construction on phase 1 of Line 1. On December 23, 2000, the project broke ground and comprehensive construction began.\n\nIn 2002, with the anticipation of an economic boom and increasing demand for urban rail transit, Wuhan Municipal Government approved the city's first long-term rail transit master plan. On July 28, 2004, the ten-station long \"light rail\" line was opened to the public and entered revenue service in August. However, low ridership discouraged the city from funding the extension project, for which ground had been broken on December 15, 2005, and a 4-year delay in construction ensued. In April, 2006, the [[National Development and Reform Commission|NDRC]] ratified a six-year construction/operation plan, but it was not until a year later on April 9, 2007 that NDRC accepted the feasibility report for line 1, phase 2 (the extension project) and approved construction on the project.\n\nIn the interim, construction began on the [[Fanhu station]] of the fully underground line 2 on November 16, 2006, as a response to the six-year plan adopted by NDRC earlier. Construction also began on the underground line 4 stations of [[Wuchang railway station]] in June, and [[Wuhan railway station]] in September, as parts of the integral capital project to revamp and construct the [[Wuhan Railway Hub System|Wuhan Railway Hub]].\n\nIn May 2007, the [[Hubei Provincial Development and Reform Commission]] (HDRC) approved preliminary designs on the Line 1, phase 2, and comprehensive construction subsequently commenced in June. On May 15, the city government approved the establishment of [[Wuhan Metro Co., Ltd]]., which would replace the [[Wuhan Rail Transit Co., Ltd]] and assume its responsibilities and benefits.\n\nOn September 12, 2007, the NDRC accepted the feasibility report to Line 2, phase 1, and preliminary designs were approved by the HDRC in December 2007. However, it was not until September 2008 that land purchases and funding were facilitated and comprehensive construction began to take place. In October 2009, drilling of the [[Yangtze River]] tunnel started.\n\nOn March 13, 2009, the NDRC accepted feasibility report to Line 4, phase 1. On May 13, 2009, the HDRC ratified preliminary designs on Line 4, phase 1. Comprehensive construction ensued on the [[Wuchang District|Wuchang]] segment of Line 4. A more ambitious urban rapid transit plan was submitted for NDRC review in October, 2009, and in late November, on-site panel investigations were conducted by [[China International Engineering Consulting Corporation]].\n\nIn February 2010 (Wuhan Metro)'s first commercial property topped out in [[Hanxi 1st Road station]]. On July 29, Line 1 phase 2 entered revenue service from [[Dijiao station|Dijiao]] to [[Dongwu Boulevard station|Dongwu Boulevard]]. Despite plans to extend the westernmost terminus to [[Jinshan Avenue]] in [[Dongxihu District]], the station was never built. A short stub with crossover tracks was constructed behind Dongwu Boulevard. [[Zhuyehai]], a station in [[Qiaokou District]], remained non-operational in spite of the existence of complete platforms. Neither exits nor staircases had been built yet. It was due to open when the Wuhan [[IKEA]] store was completed in late 2014.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=zh:\u8f7b\u8f68\u4e8c\u671f\u589e\u8bbe\u7af9\u53f6\u6d77\u7ad9 |url=http://hb.qq.com/a/20090531/000131.htm |language=Chinese}}</ref>\n\nA revised and more detailed construction plan was accepted by the NDRC on January 31, 2011. The plan specified the city's plan to complete construction on Line 3, 4, 6, 7 and 8 before 2017. Beginning on March 1, Line 1 subdivided its fare zones from 3 to 5 and lowered maximum fare from 5 CNY / ride to 4 CNY / ride. [[Wuhan Tong]] cardholders will receive a 20 percent discount on single ride fares.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u8f7b\u8f68\u7968\u4ef7\u4e0b\u8c03 |url=http://www.hb.xinhuanet.com/newscenter/2011-03/03/content_22188105.htm |language=Chinese}}</ref> On April 9, Line 1 welcomed its 100,000,000th customer, who was awarded a one-year pass to the Metro.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u8f7b\u8f68\u5ba2\u6d41\u91cf\u4eca\u65e5\u7a81\u78341\u4ebf |url=http://news.cnxianzai.com/2011/04/324488.html |language=Chinese}}</ref> On September 9, preliminary designs on Line 4, phase 2 ([[Hanyang District|Hanyang]] segment) was approved by HDRC.\n\nOn February 17, 2012, the NDRC accepted a feasibility report on line 3, phase 1, the fourth line in Wuhan Metro's grid and the first to cross the [[Han River (Yangtze River tributary)|Han River]], connecting the boroughs of [[Hankou]] and [[Hanyang District|Hanyang]]. A feasibility report to Line 6\u2014the second Hankou-Hanyang connection\u2014was also approved by the NDRC on December 21, 2012. Seven days later, line 2 entered revenue service, connecting some of the most populated areas of Hankou, Wuchang, and the [[Optics Valley of China|Optics Valley]].\n\nOn April 12, 2013, the NDRC granted acceptance to a feasibility report of Line 8, phase 1, which connects Hankou and Wuchang via the [[Second Wuhan Yangtze River Bridge|Second Yangtze River Bridge]] corridor. Construction began in June 2013 and was completed in December 2017.\n\nOn January 23, 2020, the entire network was shut down, along with all other public transport in the city, including intercity rail and air travel, to halt the spread of the coronavirus outbreak.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51215348|title=Virus-hit Chinese city shuts public transport|date=2020-01-23|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-01-23|language=en-GB}}</ref> \n\nOn 28 March 2020, six lines (Line 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 7) resume to operation, after two-month [[2020 Hubei lockdown|lockdown]].<ref name=\"resume\"/>\n===Timeline of service expansion===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Segment description\n!Date opened\n!Station(s)\n!# of new stations\n!Length (km)\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 1\n|{{date|2004-7-28}}\n|Zongguan \u2014 Huangpu Road\n|10{{NoteTag|in which, Taipingyang Station was postponed to open on {{date|2006-4-8}}.}}\n|9.769\n|-\n|Phase \u2161 of Line 1\n|{{date|2010-7-29}}\n| Dongwu Boulevard \u2014 Zongguan;<br> Huangpu Road \u2014 Dijiao\n|16{{NoteTag|in which, Zhuyehai Station was postponed to open on {{date|2014-9-17}}.<ref>[http://qzgh.qiaokou.gov.cn/qkxw/bmdt/201409/t20140917_139172.shtml \u8f7b\u8f68\u7af9\u53f6\u6d77\u7ad9\u5b9c\u5bb6\u8054\u5eca\u6865\u6295\u5165\u4f7f\u7528 (Zhuyehai station opened)]</ref>}}\n|18.494\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 2\n|{{date|2012-12-28}}\n| Jinyintan \u2014 Optics Valley Square\n|21\n|27.152\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 4<ref>[http://cjweek.cjn.cn/html/2013-12/27/content_5269051.htm Section one of Metro Line 4 opens]</ref>\n|{{date|2013-12-28}}\n| Wuchang Railway Station \u2014 Wuhan Railway Station\n|15\n|17.974\n|-\n|Hankou North extension of Line 1\n|{{date|2014-5-28}}\n|  Dijiao \u2014 Hankou North\n|3\n|5.555 \n|-\n|Phase \u2161 of Line 4\n|{{date|2014-12-28}}\n| Huangjinkou \u2014 Wuchang Railway Station\n|13\n|15.429\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 3<ref name=\"Line 3\">{{cite news|script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u5373\u5c06\u5730\u94c1\u6210\u73af \"\u73af\u91d1\u65f6\u4ee3\"\u91cd\u6784\u5546\u4e1a\u5730\u7406  |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/house/wh/2015-12/24/c_1117562445.htm |work=\u957f\u6c5f\u65e5\u62a5 |language=Chinese |date=2015-12-24 |accessdate=2015-12-24 }}</ref>\n|{{date|2015-12-28}}\n|Zhuanyang Boulevard \u2014 Hongtu Boulevard\t\n|24\n|29.660\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 6\n| rowspan=\"2\"|{{date|2016-12-28}}<ref name=\"\u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1\u673a\u573a\u7ebf\u53ca6\u53f7\u7ebf\u4eca\u65e5\u5f00\u901a \u6e56\u5317\u79fb\u52a8\u5168\u9762\u5e03\u5c40\u7f51\u7edc\u8986\u76d6\">[http://tech.cnr.cn/techgd/20161228/t20161228_523405232.shtml  \u6b66\u6c49\u5730\u94c1\u673a\u573a\u7ebf\u53ca6\u53f7\u7ebf\u4eca\u65e5\u5f00\u901a \u6e56\u5317\u79fb\u52a8\u5168\u9762\u5e03\u5c40\u7f51\u7edc\u8986\u76d6]</ref>\n|Jinyinhu Park \u2014 Dongfeng Motor Corporation\t\n|27\n|35.512\n|-\n|Northern extension of Line 2{{NoteTag|also known as Airport Line }}\n|Tianhe International Airport \u2014 Jinyintan\t\n|7\n|19.957\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 8\n| rowspan=\"3\"|{{date|2017-12-26}}\n|Jintan Road \u2014 Liyuan\t\n|12\n|16.204\n|-\n|Yangluo Line\n|Houhu Boulevard \u2014 Jintai\n|16\n|34.575\n|-\n|Jinghe extension of Line 1\n|Dongwu Boulevard \u2014 Jinghe\n|3\n|4.118\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 7\n| rowspan=\"2\"|{{date|2018-10-1}}<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=http://hb.qq.com/a/20181001/003195.htm#p=1|website=www.xinhuanet.com|script-title=zh:\u6b66\u6c49\u957f\u6c5f\u516c\u94c1\u96a7\u9053\u4eca\u65e5\u5f00\u901a 7\u53f7\u7ebf\u300111\u53f7\u7ebf\u8bd5\u8fd0\u8425|access-date=2017-12-26}}</ref>\n|Garden Expo North \u2014 Yezhihu\n|19\n|30.413\n|-\n|Phase \u2160 of Line 11\n|Optics Valley Railway Station \u2014 Zuoling\n|13\n|18.744\n|-\n|Southern extension of Line 7\n|{{date|2018-12-28}}\n|Yezhihu \u2014 Qinglongshan Ditiexiaozhen\n|7\n|16.550\n|-\n|Southern extension of Line 2\n|{{date|2019-2-19}}\n|Optics Valley Square \u2014 Fozuling\n|10\n|13.195\n|-\n|Wsetern extension of Line 4<ref name=cjn201909>{{cite web|url=http://news.cjn.cn/sywh/201909/t3460424.htm|title=\u5b9a\u4e86\uff01\u5730\u94c1\u8521\u7538\u7ebf25\u65e5\u4e0a\u53489\u65f6\u5f00\u901a|date=2019-09-23}}</ref>\n|{{date|2019-9-25}}\n|  Bailin \u2014 Huangjinkou\n|9\n|16.288\n|-\n|Phase \u2162 of Line 8<ref name=Wuhan8-3>{{cite web|url=https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/3LnB6Rl_lBp71IWU5fBITA|title=\u660e\u65e59\u70b9\uff0c\u6b66\u6c49\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a8\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e09\u671f\u5de5\u7a0b\u5f00\u901a\u8bd5\u8fd0\u8425|work=Wuhan Metro Operation|date=2019-11-05}}</ref>\n|{{date|2019-11-6}}\n|Yezhihu \u2014 Military Athletes' Village\n|3\n|4.832\n|}\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n==Network==\n{{center|[[File:Wuhan Metro System Map.svg|750px]]}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;text-align:center\"\n|-\n! class=\"unsortable\" colspan=\"100\" style=\"width:450px; \"|Current system\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"text\"|Line Name\n! class=\"unsortable\" colspan=\"2\"|Termini\n! Opened\n! Last extension\n! | Length<ref name=\u7968\u52a1\u89c4\u5b9a>{{Cite web |url =https://www.wuhanrt.com/public_forward.aspx??url=public_content_page.aspx?newid=5668a9d3-2609-4318-86dd-7b4d438be0e5&dtag=menu_motion_1|title =Ticketing regulations |publisher =Wuhan Metro Group Co., Ltd.|date =2019-11-05}}</ref>\n! | Stations\n! | Layout\n|- \n|style=\"text-align:center;; background:#{{WHM color|1}}\" | '''[[Line 1, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 1</span>]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"|{{Link-zh|Jinghe Station|\u5f84\u6cb3\u7ad9|Jinghe}}\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"|{{stl|WHM|Hankou North}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{date|2004-07-28}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |{{date|2017-12-26}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" |{{convert|37.936|km|mi||abbr=on}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | 32\n|style=\"text-align:center;\" | Elevated\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:center;; background:#{{WHM color|2}}\" | '''[[Line 2, Wuhan Metro|<span STYLE=\" color:white\">Line 2</span>]]'''\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{stl|WHM|Tianhe International Airport}}\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:225px;\"| {{Link-zh|F