nished on October 12, 1998.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mta.info/nyct/facts/ffhist.htm|title=New York City Transit - History and Chronology|last=|first=|date=|website=mta.info|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Authority|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021019203759/http://www.mta.info/nyct/facts/ffhist.htm|archive-date=October 19, 2002|url-status=dead|access-date=September 18, 2016|df=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/10/13/nyregion/beating-deadline-normal-service-returns-for-the-nos-2-and-3-subway-lines.html|title=Beating Deadline, Normal Service Returns for the Nos. 2 and 3 Subway Lines|last=Lueck|first=Thomas J.|date=October 13, 1998|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 17, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> During the reconstruction, many {{NYCS|2}} trains were rerouted via the [[IRT Lexington Avenue Line]], while the {{NYCS|3}} trains were rerouted to the [[137th Street\u2013City College (IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line)|137th Street\u2013City College]] station on the [[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]]. Each of the two Lenox Avenue Line tracks were alternately taken out of service and supplemental shuttle bus service connecting to other lines in the area were provided for much of this time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/12/nyregion/repairs-to-lenox-ave-tunnel-to-affect-many-subway-lines.html|title=Repairs to Lenox Ave. Tunnel To Affect Many Subway Lines|last=Newman|first=Andy|date=December 12, 1997|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=July 31, 2013|page=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejoekorner.com/brochures/index-lenox-rehab.html|title=Lenox Rehab '98 2 3 Lenox Line Service Guide March 2-October 1998|last=|first=|date=1998|website=thejoekorner.com|publisher=New York City Transit|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=November 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Station layout==\n{{stack|float=right|\n{{NYCS 2-tracked side platform station\n|1=125th Street\n|l1=125 St\n|2=Central Park North\u2013110th Street\n|l2=110 St\n|code=IRT Lenox Avenue Line\n|color=red\n|textcolor=white\n|deg=330\n}}\n}}\n{|table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=3\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 valign=top|'''G'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=100 valign=top|Street Level\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;\" width=400 valign=top|Exit/ Entrance\n|-\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=50 rowspan=4 valign=top|'''P<br>Platform level'''\n|style=\"border-top:solid 1px gray;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;border-bottom:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|<small>[[Side platform]], doors will open on the right</small>\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=100|<span style=\"color:#{{NYCS color|red}}\">'''Northbound'''\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;\" width=400|\u2190 {{rint|newyork|2}} toward [[Wakefield\u2013241st Street (IRT White Plains Road Line)|Wakefield\u2013241st Street]] <small>([[125th Street (IRT Lenox Avenue Line)|125th Street]])</small><br>\u2190 {{rint|newyork|3}} toward [[Harlem\u2013148th Street (IRT Lenox Avenue Line)|Harlem\u2013148th Street]] <small>(125th Street)</small>\n|-\n|<span style=\"color:#{{NYCS color|red}}\">'''Southbound'''\n|<span style=color:white>\u2192</span> {{rint|newyork|2}} toward [[Flatbush Avenue\u2013Brooklyn College (IRT Nostrand Avenue Line)|Flatbush Avenue\u2013Brooklyn College]] <small>([[110th Street (IRT Lenox Avenue Line)|110th Street]])</small> \u2192<br><span style=color:white>\u2192</span> {{rint|newyork|3}} toward [[New Lots Avenue (IRT New Lots Line)|New Lots Avenue]] ([[Times Square\u201342nd Street (IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line)|Times Square]] late nights) <small>(110th Street)</small> \u2192\n|-\n|style=\"border-bottom:solid 1px gray;border-top:solid 2px black;border-right:solid 2px black;border-left:solid 2px black;text-align:center;\" colspan=2|<small>[[Side platform]], doors will open on the right</small>\n|}\nThe station has two tracks and two [[side platform]]s. It features extensive mosaics featuring Harlem history and famous African-Americans. It was fully renovated as part of the 1998 Lenox Avenue subway reconstruction project. [[Fare control]] is at platform level. There are no crossovers or crossunders between the two side platforms to allow free transfer between directions. The reconstruction project gave this station all new wall tile and restored the \"116\" terra cotta wall cartouches as well as to combat a major water seepage problem along the Lenox Avenue Line.\n\nThe artworks here are ''Harlem Timeline'' (Willie Birch, 1995) and ''Minton's Playhouse/Movers and Shakers'' (Vincent Smith, 1999).\n\n===Exits===\n* One stair, NW corner of Lenox Avenue and West 116th Street (southbound only)<ref name=\"MTAMaps-2015\">{{cite web|url=http://web.mta.info/maps/neighborhoods/mn/M18_harlem_east_harlem_2015.pdf|title=MTA Neighborhood Maps: Harlem/East Harlem|last=|first=|date=2015|website=mta.info|publisher=[[Metropolitan Transportation Authority]]|accessdate=December 30, 2016}}</ref>\n* One stair, SW corner of Lenox Avenue and West 116th Street (southbound only)<ref name=\"MTAMaps-2015\"/>\n* One stair, NE corner of Lenox Avenue and West 116th Street (northbound only)<ref name=\"MTAMaps-2015\"/>\n* One stair, SE corner of Lenox Avenue and West 116th Street (northbound only)<ref name=\"MTAMaps-2015\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|116th Street (IRT Lenox Avenue Line)|position=left}}\n* {{NYCS ref|http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/stations?199:3151|IRT White Plains Road Line|116th Street}}\n* nycsubway.org \u2014 [http://www.nycsubway.org/perl/artwork_show?26 Minton's Playhouse/Movers and Shakers Artwork by Vincent Smith (1999)]\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20141203073216/http://www.stationreporter.net/2train.htm 2 Train]\n* Station Reporter \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20141006181936/http://www.stationreporter.net/3train.htm 3 Train]\n* The Subway Nut \u2014 [http://www.subwaynut.com/irt/116n2/index.php 116th Street Pictures]\n* MTA's Arts For Transit \u2014 [https://web.archive.org/web/20110606070649/http://mta.info/mta/aft/permanentart/permart.html?agency=nyct&line=2&station=20&xdev=2145 116th Street (IRT Lenox Avenue Line)]\n* [https://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&ll=40.801352,-73.95171&spn=0.004061,0.013379&z=17&layer=c&cbll=40.802046,-73.949732&panoid=CfvxzufGQx0EqbJzDiGwVg&cbp=12,157,,0,4.64 116th Street entrance from Google Maps Street View]\n* [http://www.google.com/maps/@40.8021715,-73.9495328,3a,75y,158.91h,84.9t/data=!3m8!1e1!3m6!1s-Ou60kcq-KQs%2FV5btKwHzJfI%2FAAAAAAAAMms%2FJq2aQgz9ubQEFpZuMbDZrlqnjAFqFvSiQCLIB!2e4!3e11!6s%2F%2Flh5.googleusercontent.com%2F-Ou60kcq-KQs%2FV5btKwHzJfI%2FAAAAAAAAMms%2FJq2aQgz9ubQEFpZuMbDZrlqnjAFqFvSiQCLIB%2Fw203-h100-p-k-no%2F!7i9728!8i4864!4m3!8m2!3m1!1e1!6m1!1e1 Platforms from Google Maps Street View]\n\n{{NYCS stations navbox by service|l2=y|l3=y}}\n{{NYCS stations navbox by line|lenox=yes}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:116th Street (Irt Lenox Avenue Line)}}\n[[Category:IRT Lenox Avenue Line stations]]\n[[Category:Harlem]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1904]]\n[[Category:1904 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:New York City Subway stations located underground]]\n", "name_user": "96.250.0.192", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/116th_Street_station_(IRT_Lenox_Avenue_Line)"}
{"title_page": "South College, Durham", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox residential college\n|university = [[University of Durham]]\n|name = South College<br />\n|photo = File:South College under construction from Van Mildert.jpg\n|image_size = 275\n|caption = College buildings seen from Van Mildert College, January 2020\n|established = 2020\n|principal =  [[Tim Luckhurst]]\n|website = http://www.dur.ac.uk/south.college/\n|coordinates = {{coord|54.762|-1.583|display=inline,title}}\n|membership = 1200 (anticipated size by 2020)\n|location_map = Durham\n|map_size = 275\n|named_after = South Road, Durham\n}}\n\n'''South College''' is a new [[Colleges of Durham University|college]] of [[Durham University]], under construction {{as of|2019|lc=y}} and due to open in autumn 2020.<ref name=southcollege>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/south.college/|title=South College|website=Durham University|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref> \n\nIt is to be located in new buildings at [[Mount Oswald]] on Elvet Hill to the south of Durham City, adjoining [[Van Mildert College]] and the new site of [[John Snow College]].<ref name=bbc170818>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-45220845|title=Durham University to spend \u00a3105m on new colleges|website=BBC News|date=17 August 2018|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe site was originally part of the grounds of [[Mount Oswald]], a country house built in 1800. In 1928, the house and grounds were converted to a golf club, which closed in 2014 and was acquired for residential development.<ref name=banks>{{cite web|url=http://www.banksgroup.co.uk/new-occupants-at-historic-mount-oswald-manor-house-through-innovative-property-guardians-project/|title=New occupants at historic Mount Oswald Manor House through innovative \u2018property guardians\u2019 project|date=27 May 2014|publisher=Banks Group|accessdate=7 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, Durham University announced that it had acquired part of the site in order to build two colleges, with construction to be carried out by a consortium led by [[Interserve]].<ref name=bbc170818 /> Construction began in September 2018, by which point it had been decided that these colleges would be one new college, South College, and a new home for [[John Snow College]] (formerly located on the university's [[Durham_University#Queen's_Campus|Queen's Campus]] in [[Stockton-on-Tees]]).<ref name=construction>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=35586|title=Construction begins on \u00a380 million Mount Oswald project|date=6 September 2018|website=Durham University|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=palatinate010719>{{cite news|url=https://www.palatinate.org.uk/decrease-in-number-of-returning-students-living-in-college-2/|title=Decrease in number of returning students living in college|first=Naomi|last=Clarke|work=Palatinate|date=1 July 2019|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref> In November 2018, Interserve pulled out of the scheme, before going into administration in March 2019.<ref name=building>{{cite news|url=https://www.building.co.uk/news/jittery-investors-tell-interserve-to-quit-durham-uni-scheme/5096552.article|title=Jittery investors tell Interserve to quit Durham uni scheme|date=15 November 2018|work=Building|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe college is anticipated to have an eventual size of 1200, with 492 living in the college.<ref name=colleges>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/experience/colleges/ourcolleges/|title=Explore the colleges|website=Durham University|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref> All accommodation is self-catered, in a mixture of single en-suite rooms and 'town houses' with shared bathroom facilities.<ref name=accommodation>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/south.college/accommodation|title=South College|website=Durham University|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, it was announced that naming of the college would be delayed in the hope that a financial donation might be attracted.<ref name=palatinate140318>{{cite news|url=https://www.palatinate.org.uk/durham-university-council-leaves-new-durham-college-unnamed-to-attract-financial-donations/|title=University Council votes to leave 17th college unnamed to attract financial donations|first=Clara|last=Gaspar|work=Palatinate|date=14 March 2018|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref> The temporary name \"South College\" was assigned pending selection of a final name, and was used in advertisements for the new college's first principal. In June 2019, [[Durham Students' Union]] assembly voted to lobby for the college to be named after the late politician and Durham graduate [[Mo Mowlam]].<ref name=mowlam>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/local/northdurham/17729167.students-to-lobby-to-name-durham-universitys-new-college-after-mo-mowlam/|title=Students to lobby to name Durham University's new college after Mo Mowlam|date=26 June 2019|access-date=8 July 2019|work=The Northern Echo}}</ref> On 1 April 2020, Durham's student newspaper ''[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]'' published an [[April Fools' Day]] joke that South College was to be named Vine College after broadcaster and Durham alumnus [[Jeremy Vine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.palatinate.org.uk/south-college-to-be-named-after-jeremy-vine/|title=South College to be named after Jeremy Vine|date=2020-04-01|website=Palatinate Online|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The actual name of the college is yet to be confirmed.\n\nOn 5 July 2019 it was announced that [[University of Kent]] academic and former [[BBC]] editor [[Tim Luckhurst]] had been appointed as the first principal of the college, to start in November 2019.<ref name=newheads>{{cite tweet|user=durham_uni|author=Durham University|number=1147151911281483778|title=We are delighted to announce the appointment of five new Heads of College who will join us in 2019/20.|date=5 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:South College and John Snow College under construction.jpg|700px|thumb|center|South College (left) and [[John Snow College]] (right) under construction in January 2020]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.dur.ac.uk/south.college/ Official website]\n\n{{University of Durham}}\n\n[[Category:Colleges of Durham University]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2020]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox residential college\n|university = [[University of Durham]]\n|name = South College<br />\n|photo = File:South College under construction from Van Mildert.jpg\n|image_size = 275\n|caption = College buildings seen from Van Mildert College, January 2020\n|established = 2020\n|principal =  [[Tim Luckhurst]]\n|website = http://www.dur.ac.uk/south.college/\n|coordinates = {{coord|54.762|-1.583|display=inline,title}}\n|membership = 1200 (anticipated size by 2020)\n|location_map = Durham\n|map_size = 275\n|named_after = South Road, Durham\n}}\n\n'''South College''' is a new [[Colleges of Durham University|college]] of [[Durham University]], under construction {{as of|2019|lc=y}} and due to open in autumn 2020.<ref name=southcollege>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/south.college/|title=South College|website=Durham University|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref> \n\nIt is to be located in new buildings at [[Mount Oswald]] on Elvet Hill to the south of Durham City, adjoining [[Van Mildert College]] and the new site of [[John Snow College]].<ref name=bbc170818>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-45220845|title=Durham University to spend \u00a3105m on new colleges|website=BBC News|date=17 August 2018|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe site was originally part of the grounds of [[Mount Oswald]], a country house built in 1800. In 1928, the house and grounds were converted to a golf club, which closed in 2014 and was acquired for residential development.<ref name=banks>{{cite web|url=http://www.banksgroup.co.uk/new-occupants-at-historic-mount-oswald-manor-house-through-innovative-property-guardians-project/|title=New occupants at historic Mount Oswald Manor House through innovative \u2018property guardians\u2019 project|date=27 May 2014|publisher=Banks Group|accessdate=7 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, Durham University announced that it had acquired part of the site in order to build two colleges, with construction to be carried out by a consortium led by [[Interserve]].<ref name=bbc170818 /> Construction began in September 2018, by which point it had been decided that these colleges would be one new college, South College, and a new home for [[John Snow College]] (formerly located on the university's [[Durham_University#Queen's_Campus|Queen's Campus]] in [[Stockton-on-Tees]]).<ref name=construction>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/news/newsitem/?itemno=35586|title=Construction begins on \u00a380 million Mount Oswald project|date=6 September 2018|website=Durham University|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref><ref name=palatinate010719>{{cite news|url=https://www.palatinate.org.uk/decrease-in-number-of-returning-students-living-in-college-2/|title=Decrease in number of returning students living in college|first=Naomi|last=Clarke|work=Palatinate|date=1 July 2019|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref> In November 2018, Interserve pulled out of the scheme, before going into administration in March 2019.<ref name=building>{{cite news|url=https://www.building.co.uk/news/jittery-investors-tell-interserve-to-quit-durham-uni-scheme/5096552.article|title=Jittery investors tell Interserve to quit Durham uni scheme|date=15 November 2018|work=Building|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe college is anticipated to have an eventual size of 1200, with 492 living in the college.<ref name=colleges>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/experience/colleges/ourcolleges/|title=Explore the colleges|website=Durham University|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref> All accommodation is self-catered, in a mixture of single en-suite rooms and 'town houses' with shared bathroom facilities.<ref name=accommodation>{{cite web|url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/south.college/accommodation|title=South College|website=Durham University|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, it was announced that naming of the college would be delayed in the hope that a financial donation might be attracted.<ref name=palatinate140318>{{cite news|url=https://www.palatinate.org.uk/durham-university-council-leaves-new-durham-college-unnamed-to-attract-financial-donations/|title=University Council votes to leave 17th college unnamed to attract financial donations|first=Clara|last=Gaspar|work=Palatinate|date=14 March 2018|access-date=8 July 2019}}</ref> The temporary name \"South College\" was assigned pending selection of a final name, and was used in advertisements for the new college's first principal. In June 2019, [[Durham Students' Union]] assembly voted to lobby for the college to be named after politician and Durham graduate [[Mo Mowlam]].<ref name=mowlam>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/news/local/northdurham/17729167.students-to-lobby-to-name-durham-universitys-new-college-after-mo-mowlam/|title=Students to lobby to name Durham University's new college after Mo Mowlam|date=26 June 2019|access-date=8 July 2019|work=The Northern Echo}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 July 2019 it was announced that [[University of Kent]] academic and former [[BBC]] editor [[Tim Luckhurst]] had been appointed as the first principal of the college, to start in November 2019.<ref name=newheads>{{cite tweet|user=durham_uni|author=Durham University|number=1147151911281483778|title=We are delighted to announce the appointment of five new Heads of College who will join us in 2019/20.|date=5 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April 2020, Durham's student newspaper ''[[Palatinate (newspaper)|Palatinate]]'' published an [[April Fools' Day]] joke that South College was to be named Vine College after broadcaster and Durham alumnus [[Jeremy Vine]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.palatinate.org.uk/south-college-to-be-named-after-jeremy-vine/|title=South College to be named after Jeremy Vine|date=2020-04-01|website=Palatinate Online|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The actual name of the college is yet to be confirmed.\n\n[[File:South College and John Snow College under construction.jpg|700px|thumb|center|South College (left) and [[John Snow College]] (right) under construction in January 2020]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.dur.ac.uk/south.college/ Official website]\n\n{{University of Durham}}\n\n[[Category:Colleges of Durham University]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2020]]\n", "name_user": "Livvylitchfield", "label": "safe", "comment": "rearranged paragraphs for clarity", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_College,_Durham"}
